<h3>Why carbon (as opposed to any other type of pollution mitigation)?</h3>
<p>Carbon is the ultimate global issue and it requires a global solution. Carbon isn’t toxic, so there is no immediate incentive to be the one guy who doesn’t drive an SUV instead of a Prius to work. Only in its global aggregation does it present catastrophic environmental harm. In the past, governments have attempted to work together to solve the issue to varying degrees of success and failure, and a permanent global solution is currently not really very effective, or certainly not effective enough at this time. A strong criticism to government run programs is the drag on the economy that punitive Cap & Trade regulations and Carbon Taxes result in. However, the other side of this equation is the drag on the economy the environmental damage costs from global warming’s adverse effects.  Governments try to gauge the two side of this equation for setting Cap & Trade / Carbon tax regulations. However, governments are less efficient than market based pricing methods. Therefore, a voluntary, market-based way to price and trade carbon is required in order to solve this menacing issue.
<br/><br/></p></div>
 
