<h3>How does the GreenCoin calculation work?</h3>
<p>This is an example of how GreenCoin is distributed within the context of renewable energy generation. GreenCoin is ultimately a measure of sequestered carbon and/or carbon that is not produced during the production of renewable energy compared to the same amount of energy produced by the aggregate global average for the exact same activity. Therefore, it is closely tied with the amount of CO2 offset that can be calculated as a consequence of utilizing renewable energy versus non-renewable energy. The current global average amount of CO2 emitted to produce 1kWh is about 527 g CO2. If a solar producer (46 g CO2/kWh) pushes 10 kWh to the grid, they’ve created power to the benefit of the grid users without the creation of 4.81 kg of CO2 entering the atmosphere ([0.527 - .0046] kg/kWh X 10 kWh = 4.81 kg). This figure has been termed Carbon-Productivity Sequestration and the units are in kg CO2.  Carbon-Productivity Sequestration differs from straight carbon sequestration in that we reward the productive event (such as renewable power production) as opposed to penalizing the emissions. This provides for a mechanism to reward economic productivity for green commerce providers as opposed to financially limiting high-emitting ones.<br/><br/></p></div>
 
 <div>
<h3>Who is responsible for GreenCoin distribution?</h3>
<p>The GreenCoin Foundation receives exactly one-half (50%) of all of the coins being mined via the traditional cryptocurrency mining method.  We have termed this as the compulsory sharing element.  The foundation aggregates the data of the producers who have effectuated carbon-productivity sequestration for that day.  We then distribute the coins received (currently about 1,369,000 per day) pro rata to all of the producers within the network. The Foundation is still in formation so the GreenCoin founders will issue the coins until the formation occurs.<br/><br/></p></div>
 

 
<div>
<h3>How does the GreenCoin mechanism effectuate global carbon emissions reduction?</h3>
<p>Each renewable producing unit that comes online shrinks the amount of CO2 calculated as being sequestered for all producers at the margin, making a GreenCoins more competitive to produce. This figure is updated and set by the GreenCoin Foundation based on a variety of widely published government and scientific reports.  To further the electric power production as an example, the current global emissions to produce 1 kWh averages to 481 grams of CO2, however, as more green power comes on line (and hopefully due to GreenCoins existence!), this global average will begin to decrease substantially. If, at some point in the future, the global average were only 250 grams CO2 per kWh and you had a system generating power at 200 grams CO2 per kWh, you are receiving only 50 grams CO2 per kWh generated which you then gets rewarded GreenCoins (this would be less than before when you were generating green power versus the 527 grams CO2 per kWh global average). This incentivizes producers to reduce their CO2 impact as much as possible to receive the most GreenCoins and continue to find ways to do so as the global problem begins to resolve.<br/><br/></p></div>
 
